Sir Robert Eric Mortimer Wheeler September 1890 July 1976 was British archaeologist and officer the British Army Over the course his career served Director both the National Museum Wales and London Museum DirectorGeneral the Archaeological Survey India and the founder and Honorary Director the Institute Archaeology London addition writing twentyfour books archaeological subjects Born Glasgow middleclass family Wheeler was raised largely Yorkshire before relocating London his teenage years After studying Classics University College London UCL began working professionally archaeology specializing the RomanoBritish period During World War volunteered for service the Royal Artillery being stationed the Western Front where rose the rank major and was awarded the Military Cross Returning Britain obtained his doctorate from UCL before taking position the National Museum Wales first Keeper Archaeology and then Director during which time oversaw excavation the Roman forts Segontium Gaer and Isca Augusta with the aid his first wife Tessa Wheeler Influenced the archaeologist Augustus Pitt Rivers Wheeler argued that excavation and the recording stratigraphic context required increasingly scientific and methodical approach developing the Wheeler Method 1926 was appointed Keeper the London Museum there oversaw reorganisation the collection successfully lobbied for increased funding and began lecturing UCL 1934 established the Institute Archaeology part the federal University London adopting the position Honorary Director this period oversaw excavations the Roman sites Lydney Park and Verulamium and the Iron Age hill fort Maiden Castle During World War rejoined the Armed Forces and rose the rank brigadier serving the North African Campaign and then the Allied invasion Italy 1944 was appointed DirectorGeneral the Archaeological Survey India through which oversaw excavations sites Harappa Arikamedu and Brahmagiri and implemented reforms the subcontinents archaeological establishment Returning Britain 1948 divided his time between lecturing for the Institute Archaeology and acting archaeological adviser Pakistans government later life his popular books cruise ship lectures and appearances radio and television particularly the BBC series Animal Vegetable Mineral helped bring archaeology mass audience Appointed Honorary Secretary the British Academy raised large sums money for archaeological projects and was appointed British representative for several UNESCO projects Wheeler recognised one the most important British archaeologists the twentieth century responsible for successfully encouraging British public interest the discipline and advancing methodologies excavation and recording Furthermore widely acclaimed major figure the establishment South Asian archaeology However many his specific interpretations archaeological sites have been discredited reinterpreted and was often criticised for bullying colleagues and sexually harassing young women Mortimer Wheeler was born September 1890 the city Glasgow Scotland was the first child the journalist Robert Mortimer Wheeler and his second wife Emily Wheeler Baynes The son tea merchant based Bristol youth Robert had considered becoming Baptist minister but instead became staunch freethinker while studying the University Edinburgh Initially working lecturer English literature Robert turned journalism after his first wife died childbirth His second wife Emily shared her husbands interest English literature and was the niece Thomas Spencer Baynes Shakespearean scholar Andrews University Their marriage was emotionally strained situation exacerbated their financial insecurity Within two years their sons birth the family moved Edinburgh where daughter named Amy was born The couple gave their two children nicknames with Mortimer being Boberic and Amy being Totsy When Wheeler was four his father was appointed chief leader writer for the Bradford Observer The family relocated Saltaire village northwest Bradford cosmopolitan city Yorkshire northeast England which was then the midst the wool trade boom Wheeler was inspired the moors surrounding Saltaire and fascinated the areas archaeology later wrote about discovering late prehistoric cupmarked stone searching for lithics Ilkley Moor and digging into barrow Baildon Moor Although suffering from ill health Emily Wheeler taught her two children with the help maid the age seven eight Mortimer remained emotionally distant from his mother instead being far closer his father whose company favoured over that other children His father had keen interest natural history and love fishing and shooting rural pursuits which encouraged Mortimer take part Robert acquired many books for his son particularly the subject art history with Wheeler loving both read and paint 1899 Wheeler joined Bradford Grammar School shortly before his ninth birthday where proceeded straight the second form 1902 Robert and Emily had second daughter whom they named Betty Mortimer showed little interest this younger sister 1905 Robert agreed take over head the London office his newspaper then renamed the Yorkshire Daily Observer and the family relocated the southeast the city December settling into house named Carlton Lodge South Croydon Road West Dulwich 1908 they moved Rollescourt Avenue nearby Herne Hill Rather than being sent for conventional education when was Wheeler was instructed educate himself spending time London where frequented The National Gallery and the Victoria and Albert Museum After passing the entrance exam his second attempt 1907 Wheeler was awarded scholarship read classical studies University College London UCL commuting daily from his parental home the university campus Bloomsbury central London UCL was taught the prominent classicist Housman During his undergraduate studies became editor the Union Magazine for which produced number illustrated cartoons Increasingly interested art decided switch from classical studies course UCLs art school the Slade School Fine Art returned his previous subject after coming the opinion that his words never became more than conventionally accomplished picture maker This interlude had adversely affected his classical studies and received second class graduating Wheeler began studying for Master Arts degree classical studies which attained 1912 During this period also gained employment the personal secretary the UCL Provost Gregory Foster although later criticised Foster for transforming the university from college the truly academic sense into hypertrophied monstrosity little like college plesiosaurus like man was also this time life that met and began relationship with Tessa Verney student then studying history UCL when they were both serving the committee the University College Literary Society During his studies Wheeler had developed his love archaeology having joined excavation Viroconium Cornoviorum RomanoBritish settlement Wroxeter 1913 Considering profession the discipline won studentship that had been established jointly the University London and the Society Antiquaries memory Augustus Wollaston Franks The prominent archaeologist Sir Arthur Evans doubled the amount money that went with the studentship Wheelers proposed project had been analyse RomanoRhenish pottery and with the grant funded trip the Rhineland Germany there studying the Roman pottery housed local museums his research into this subject was never published this period there were very few jobs available within British archaeology the later archaeologist Stuart Piggott related the young Wheeler was looking for professional job where the profession had yet created 1913 Wheeler secured position junior investigator for the English Royal Commission Historical Monuments who were embarking project assess the state all structures the nation that predated 1714 part this was first sent Stebbing Essex assess Late Medieval buildings although once that was accomplished focused studying the RomanoBritish remain