 the Italian Riviera reach Caporetto where had been sent bolster the Italian troops against German and AustroHungarian advance the Russian Republic removed itself from the war the German Army refocused its efforts the Western Front and March 1918 Wheelers brigade was ordered leave Italy getting train from Castelfranco Vieux Rouen France Back the Western Front the brigade was assigned the 2nd Division again part Julian Byngs Third Army reaching stable area the front April Here Wheeler was engaged artillery fire for several months before the British went the offensive August August between the ruined villages Achiet and Sapignies led expedition which captured two German field guns while under heavy fire from castle mound was later awarded the Military Cross for this action For conspicuous gallantry and initiative While making reconnaissance saw two enemy field guns limbered without horses within 300 yards the outpost line returned for two sixhorse teams and under heavy fire full view the enemy successfully brought back both guns his battery position and turned them the enemy did fine work Wheeler continued part the British forces pushing westward until the German surrender November 1918 receiving mention dispatches November was not demobilised for several months instead being stationed Pulheim Germany until March during this time wrote his earlier research RomanoRhenish pottery making use access local museums before returning London July 1919 Reverting his permanent rank lieutenant September Wheeler was finally discharged from service September 1921 retaining the rank major returning London Wheeler moved into topfloor flat near Gordon Square with his wife and child returned working for the Royal Commission examining and cataloguing the historic structures Essex doing produced his first publication academic paper Colchesters Roman Balkerne Gate which was published the Transactions the Essex Archaeological Society 1920 soon followed this with two papers the Journal Roma