donation from the wealthy shipowner William Reardon Smith and appointed Smith the museums treasurer and also travelled Whitehall London where successfully urged the British Treasury provide further funding for the museum result construction the museums new building was able continue and was officially opened King George 1927 Upon the retirement the Keeper the London Museum Harmon Oates Wheeler was invited fill the vacancy had been considering return London for some time and eagerly agreed taking the post which was based Lancaster House the Jamess area July 1926 Wales many felt that Wheeler had simply taken the directorship the National Museum advance his own career prospects and that had abandoned them when better offer came along Wheeler himself disagreed believing that had left Fox the Museum his obvious successor and that the reforms had implemented would therefore continue The position initially provided Wheeler with annual salary 600 which resulted decline living standards for his family who moved into flat near Victoria Station Tessas biographer Carr later commented that together the Wheelers professionalized the London Museum Wheeler expressed his opinion that the museum had cleaned expurgated and catalogued general turned from junk shop into tolerably rational institution Focusing reorganising the exhibits and developing more efficient method cataloguing the artefacts also authored Short Guide the Collections before using the items the museum write three books London and the Vikings London and the Saxons and London and the Romans Upon his arrival the Treasury allocated the museum annual budget 5000 which Wheeler deemed insufficient for its needs 1930 Wheeler persuaded them increase that budget highlighted increasing visitor numbers publications and acquisitions well rise the number educational projects With this additional funding was able employ more staff and increase his own annual salary 900 Soon after joining the museum Wheeler was elected the council the Society Antiquaries Through the Society became involved the debate who should finance archaeological supervision building projects Greater London his argument was that the City London Corporation should provide the funding although 1926 was agreed that the Society itself would employ director excavation based Lancaster House take the position Also involved the largely moribund Royal Archaeological Institute Wheeler organised its relocation Lancaster House 1927 Wheeler took unpaid lectureship University College London where established graduate diploma course archaeology one the first enroll was Stuart Piggott 1928 Wheeler curated exhibit UCL Recent Work British Archaeology for which attracted much press attention Wheeler was keen continue archaeological fieldwork outside London undertaking excavations every year from 1926 1939 After completing his excavation the Carlaeon amphitheatre 1928 began fieldwork the Roman settlement and temple Lydney Park Gloucestershire having been invited the aristocratic landowner Charles Bathurst was during these investigations that Wheeler personally discovered the Lydney Hoard coinage Wheeler and his wife jointly published their excavation report 1932 Report the Excavation the Prehistoric Roman and PostRoman Site Lydney Park Gloucestershire which Piggott noted had set the pattern for all Wheelers future excavation reports From there Wheeler was invited direct Society Antiquaries excavation the Roman settlement Verulamium which existed land recently acquired the Corporation Albans took this role for four seasons from 1930 1933 before leaving fifth season excavation under the control the archaeologist Kathleen Kenyon and the architect Lowther Wheeler enjoyed the opportunity excavate civilian opposed military site and also liked its proximity his home London was particularly interested searching for preRoman Iron Age oppidum the site noting that the existence nearby Catuvellauni settlement was attested both classical texts and numisma