 the view that was the least political mortals Despite not taking strong interest politics Wheeler was described his biographer natural conservative for instance during his youth was strongly critical the Suffragettes and their cause greater legal rights for women Nevertheless was usually happy advance young women professionally something that may have been based largely his sexual attraction toward them expressed little interest his relatives later life saw reason have social relationship with people purely the basis family ties Wheeler was married three times May 1914 Wheeler married Tessa Verney Tessa became accomplished archaeologist and they collaborated until she died 1936 Their only child Michael Mortimer Wheeler was born January 1915 became barrister Following Tessas death 1939 Wheeler married Mavis Vere Cole widow the prankster Horace Vere Cole Their relationship was strained Coles diaries revealed that Wheeler physically hit her when she annoyed him 1945 Mortimer Wheeler married his third wife Margaret Kim Collingridge Although they became estranged 1956 Collingridges Catholicism prevented divorce Meanwhile Wheeler was well known for his conspicuous promiscuity favouring young women for onenight stands many whom were his students was further known for having casual sex public places That behaviour led much emotional suffering among his various wives and mistresses which was aware result his behaviour later archaeologist Gabriel Moshenska informed reporter from the Daily Mail that Wheeler had developed reputation bit groper and sex pest and incredible bully well Jacquetta Hawkes 1982 Wheeler has been termed the most famous British archaeologist the twentieth century archaeologists Gabriel Moshenska and Tim SchadlaHall Highlighting his key role encouraging interest archaeology throughout British society they stated that his mastery public archaeology was founded his keen eye for value and showmans willingness packageand sell the past This was issue about which Wheeler felt very strongly writing his obituary for the Biographical Memoirs Fellows the Royal Society the English archaeologist Stuart Piggott noted that Wheeler placed great importance the archaeologists obligation the public whose support the prosecution his subject ultimately depended Piggott believed that Wheelers greatest impact was the great innovator field techniques comparing him this respect PittRivers Piggott stated that the importance Wheelers contribution archaeological technique enormous and farreaching lies the fact that the early 1920s not only appreciated and understood what PittRivers had done but saw that his work could used basis for adaptation development and improvement Carr stated that was for his methodological developments oft termed the Wheeler Method that Wheeler was best known this she contrasted him with those archaeologists who were best known for their associations with specific archaeological site such Arthur Evans and Knossos Leonard Woolley and Wheeler was well known for his publications archaeological matters Carr stated that both Wheeler and his first wife emphasised technical rigour and full presentation materials unearthed well literary discussion their meaning calculated appeal larger audience Focusing Wheelers publications regarding South Asian archaeology Sudeshna Guha noted that produced assemblage imageobjects that embodied the precision demanded from excavation photographyMallowan noted that Immediate and swift presentation results was more important him than profound scholarship although his critical sense made him conscious that was necessary maintain high standards and would approve nothing that was slipshod Jacquetta Hawkes commented that made errors his interpretation the archaeological evidence because was sometimes too sure being right too ready accept his own authority She asserted that while Wheeler was not original thinker had vision human history that enabled him see each discovery its traces however small its widest significance Dilip Chakrabarti 1982 Piggott claimed that Wheelers appointment DirectorGeneral the Archaeological Survey India represented the most remarkable archaeological achievement his career enormous challenge accepted and surmounted the autocratic and authoritarian terms within which could best deploy his powers administrator and excavator other archaeologist the time seems fair remark could have come near attaining his command incisive strategy and often ruthless tactics which won him the bewildered admiration and touching devotion his Indian staff The Indian archaeologist Dilip Chakrabarti later stated that Wheelers accomplishments while India were considerable particularly given the sociopolitical turmoil independence and partition Chakrabarti stated that Wheeler had contributed South Asian archaeology various ways establishing total view the regions development from the Palaeolithic onward introducing new archaeological techniques and methodologies the subcontinent and encouraging Indian universities begin archaeological research Ultimately Chakrabarti was the opinion that Wheeler had prepared the archaeology the subcontinent for its transition modernity the postPartition period Similarly Peter Johansen praised Wheeler for systematising and professionalising Indian archaeology and for instituting clearly defined body techniques and methods for field and laboratory work and training Wheelers death Sankalia Deccan College Pune described him well known among Old World archaeologists the United States particularly for his book Archaeology from the Earth and his studies the Indus Valley Civilisation its 2013 obituary the English archaeologist Mick Aston British Archaeology magazine the publication the Council for British Archaeology described Aston the Mortimer Wheeler our times because despite the strong differences between their personalities both had done much bring archaeology the British public However writing 2011 Moshenska and SchadlaHall assert